text
@d96 2
a97 2
install54.iso) and "boot only" (for installing from a network file
source, named cd54.iso) ISOs are provided for these platforms.
a106 9
However, ISO file installation is NOT the optimum
installation method for many people.
It is still usually faster and simpler to download the boot media and
then install just the portions needed.
However, for those who wish to do a number of installations, or can not
figure out how to drop ten files on a CD-ROM or set up a local HTTP/FTP
server, ISOs are available.

<p>
d120 5
a124 6
For those that need a bootable CD for their system, bootdisk ISO images
<!-- XXXrelease -->
(named <tt>cd54.iso</tt>) are available for a number of platforms which
will then permit the rest of the system to be installed via HTTP/FTP.  These
ISO images are only a few megabytes in size, and contain just the installation
tools, not the actual file sets.
d156 15
a170 7
<table border=0 width="90%"><tr><td nowrap bgcolor="#EEEEEE"><pre>
  $ <b>sha256 -c SHA256</b>
</pre></td></tr></table>

The OpenBSD project does not digitally sign releases.  The above command only
detects accidental damage, not malicious tampering.  If the men in black suits
are out to get you, they're going to get you.
