<li><a href="#SelectHW"  >3.5 - Selecting Hardware</a>
d180 1
a180 1
<li><b>Let the application chose the hardware.</b>
d185 1
a185 2
<p>
<li><b>Identify your bottlenecks.</b>    
d191 1
a191 2
<p>
<li><b>Keep it simple.</b>
a195 1
<p>
d197 1
a197 1
implement a production system.</b> 
d200 1
a200 1
both how it works <i>and how it fails</i> is foolish.
d202 1
a202 2
<p>
<li><b>Use multiple disks.</b>
d206 1
a206 1
spindles, you will get more reliability and faster data access with RAID.
d208 1
a208 2
<p>
<li><b>Break up large blocks of storage.</b>
d220 1
a220 30
<p>
<li><b>Use SCSI if you need very high disk performance.</b>
Using high end SCSI disks (higher cost 10k RPM to 15k RPM disks), you can
achieve better performance than high-end IDE disks, when matched
with a appropriate and supported SCSI adapter.
Conversely, if you are using medium or low end or older SCSI disks, this
is a waste of money, and IDE will serve you just as well, if not better.
Be realistic: a top-speed disk system on your simple firewall is likely
to cause you far more problems and the "performance" will never be seen.

<p>If you are building a server, and you need more than one drive,
you may want to consider SCSI.
IDE limits you to two disks per controller.
Concurrent access to these two disks may have a negative
impact on the I/O performance of these disks.
Wide SCSI limits you to 15 per channel, and has better support for
concurrent access than IDE.
While SCSI costs more, the flexibility and performance can justify these
costs in some environments.

<p>
<li><b>Use ECC or parity RAM.</b>
Parity adds some functionality to see if the data in RAM has been
corrupted.  ECC extends this functionality and attempts to correct
some bit corruption errors on the fly.
Obviously, the rest of your system must support parity or ECC before
you gain any benefit.

<p>
<li><b>Avoid cheap network adapters.</b>
d251 1
a251 1
<li><b>Processor</b>
d253 1
a253 1
Yes, OpenBSD will run on a 25MHz 80386, but you won't want to do
d259 1
a259 1
X actually runs pretty well on a slower machine once running, but it
d262 2
a263 2
<li><b>32M RAM or better.</b>
If you wish to run X, 64M would be a better starting point.
d301 2
a302 2
Brand new, cutting-edge hardware is often not yet supported by OpenBSD,
so for your first OpenBSD system, a slightly older machine is
d308 2
a309 2
Some popular applications, such as Mozilla, seemingly can use as much
processor and memory as you can throw at the system.
d324 1
a324 1
